## 2. ML/DL in Phage Virology

## 2.1 Overview: why phages are a special ML/DL domain

Bacteriophages occupy a unique position in virology research. They are the most abundant biological entities on Earth, shape microbial communities, and offer therapeutic potential against multidrug-resistant bacteria. At the same time, phage research has become a leading testbed for machine learning (ML) and deep learning (DL) because it combines large genomic datasets, dense phage–host interaction matrices, and experimentally tractable assays that enable rapid iteration between model and experiment.[[pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40359589/)]

Recent reviews emphasize that phage research has undergone a "revolution" driven by neural networks applied to metagenomic data, pre-trained language models for sequence analysis, and new bioinformatics tools for viral genome reconstruction. These advances have transformed phage discovery, host prediction, protein function annotation, lifecycle classification, and phage therapy design. Because phages can be propagated in vitro, labels for infection phenotypes are relatively easy to generate, and experimental validation cycles are short. This makes phages a natural "sandbox" for mechanistic ML/DL, where models can be explicitly aligned with biological processes such as adsorption, receptor binding, replication, and lysis.[[pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12149144/)]

## 2.2 Data types and data sizes

Phage ML/DL studies rely on several main data types:

**Genomic and metagenomic sequences**  
Whole phage genomes, metagenome-assembled viral genomes (vMAGs), and metagenomic contigs form the core data for most ML/DL applications. Public databases such as IMG/PH, PhageDB, and PHROG contain thousands to tens of thousands of phage genomes and associated annotations. Metagenomic datasets can be much larger, with millions of reads and thousands of vMAGs reconstructed from gut, soil, or marine samples.[[reddit](https://www.reddit.com/r/ketoscience/comments/1pc1b2l/longread_metagenomics_reveals_phage_dynamics_in/)]

**Phage–host interaction matrices**  
High-throughput experiments produce phage × host infectivity matrices, where each entry indicates infection, no infection, or efficiency of plating (EOP). These matrices are often used as training labels for host-range prediction models. Public resources include phage–host interaction databases with 100–1000 strains and phages, and combined datasets aggregating data from multiple sources.[[research.kuleuven](https://research.kuleuven.be/portal/en/project/3E210935)]

**Protein sequences and functional annotations**  
Phage proteins are analyzed using protein language models, homology detection tools, and functional classifiers. Databases such as PHROG and EFAM contain thousands of phage protein families and functional annotations. Protein sequences are often millions of residues in total across metagenomic datasets.[[openreview](https://openreview.net/forum?id=IEZjjDX0iC)]

**Phenotypic and experimental data**  
Time-kill curves, adsorption rates, yield curves, and plaque morphology data provide quantitative phenotypes for infection outcomes. These data are smaller in size (tens to hundreds of experiments) but highly informative for mechanistic models.[[highlightsin](https://highlightsin.org/index.php/bioscience/article/view/203/0)]

## 2.3 Methodological approaches

Current ML/DL methods in phage virology fall into several broad categories:

**Classical ML for host prediction and classification**  
Random forests, gradient boosting, and SVMs are used on k-mer features, gene presence/absence matrices, and protein-informed features to predict host species, strain, or lifestyle. Protein–protein interaction (PPI) features have been shown to improve accuracy, with 78–94% host-range prediction accuracy across Salmonella and Escherichia phages. CatBoost models incorporating ESM2 embeddings have been developed for receptor-binding protein (RBP) detection.[[pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41174147/)]

**Deep learning on sequences and metagenomes**  
CNNs and transformers applied to raw nucleotide or amino-acid sequences are used for phage classification, host prediction, and lifecycle prediction. DeepPL, an NLP-based tool, predicts phage lifecycles from nucleotide sequences using deep learning. Pre-trained language models such as BERT, ProtT5, ProT5, ESM2, TMVec, and CARP are used to generate protein embeddings for phage homology detection and function prediction.[[bacteriophage](https://www.bacteriophage.news/computational-function-prediction-of-bacteria-and-phage-proteins/)]

**Phage–host interaction prediction from metagenomic profiles**  
Novel deep learning frameworks predict phage–host interactions (PHIs) directly from taxonomic profiles of metagenomic data, without requiring assembly. PHILM (Phage-Host Interaction Learning from Metagenomic profiles) uses deep learning to predict PHIs from metagenomic taxonomic profiles and outperforms co-abundance-based approaches. On a dataset of 7,016 stool samples, PHILM identified 90% more genus-level PHIs than traditional assembly-based methods. Similar frameworks, such as phiNODE, use neural ordinary differential equations for PHI prediction.[[pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40666868/)]

**Protein language models and functional annotation**  
Protein language models (pLMs) are compared for remote homology detection in phage proteins, with models trained on larger databases generally performing better. Tools such as DeepPL, PHROG-based classifiers, and command-line pLM-based function predictors provide scores for phage protein function prediction. New methods integrate ESM2 embeddings with structural modeling to predict RBP binding affinity and specificity.[[amr-conference](https://amr-conference.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/Lu.pdf)]

**Generative and design models**  
AI models have been used to generate synthetic bacteriophage genomes. Two AI models (Evo 1 and Evo 2) generated approximately 300 putative phage genomes, of which 16 produced viable viruses that could infect _E. coli_. Some AI-generated phages killed _E. coli_ faster than ΦX174, and cocktails of AI-generated phages overcame phage-resistant strains. This represents the first successful generation of entire working viral genomes by AI, with implications for phage therapy design.[[sciencenews](https://www.sciencenews.org/article/ai-genome-bacteria-phage)]

**Mechanistic and layered models**  
Layered ML models align with infection stages: binding to receptors, infection, replication, and spread. These models integrate CRISPR-Cas systems, structural proteins, bacterial membrane proteins, and immunity proteins to better understand phage-bacteria interactions and develop phage cocktails. AI approaches are advancing the study of phage-host interactions in ways that enable more effective phage therapy recommendations. MoEPH (Mixture-of-Experts for Phage-Host prediction) integrates transformer-based protein embeddings with domain-specific statistical descriptors for health informatics. MoEPH achieves 99.6% accuracy on balanced datasets and 31% improvement on imbalanced data.[[frontiersin](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/cellular-and-infection-microbiology/articles/10.3389/fcimb.2025.1611857/full)]

**Tool availability and integration**  
Many tools are available as open-source command-line packages or web platforms. What the Phage (WtP) is an easy-to-use multitool approach for phage identification combined with annotation and classification downstream strategy. PhageScanner streamlines data collection for genomic and metagenomic datasets, model training, and testing. CRISPRi-ART highlights what proteins are most important for phage infection programmably.[[mult1fractal.github](https://mult1fractal.github.io/wtp-documentation/)]

## 2.4 Target resolution

ML/DL studies in phage virology target several levels of resolution:

- **Host type and strain**: phage host species, genus, or strain prediction[[tandfonline](https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/23311916.2021.1958666)]
    
- **Lifestyle**: lytic vs temperate, virulence factors, and lysogeny-related gene prediction[[pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/40359589/)]
    
- **Receptor identity**: phage receptor-binding protein and target receptor prediction[[ipo.lbl](https://ipo.lbl.gov/2025/08/20/ai-assisted-prediction-of-phage-host-absorption-factors-2025-150/)]
    
- **Infection outcome**: binary or graded infectivity, EOP, adsorption probability, replication yield, and lysis timing[[biblio.ugent](https://biblio.ugent.be/publication/8733425)]
    
- **Phage cocktail performance**: predicted success of phage combinations against bacterial communities, including synergy/antagonism[[frontiersin](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/cellular-and-infection-microbiology/articles/10.3389/fcimb.2025.1611857/full)]
    
- **Phage function**: protein function annotation, homology detection, and metabolic pathway involvement[[openreview](https://openreview.net/forum?id=IEZjjDX0iC)]
    

## 2.5 Tool availability and experimental integration

Tools are increasingly open and integrable:

- **Open-source command-line tools**: What the Phage, PhageScanner, PHROG-based classifiers, pLM-based function predictors[[journals.asm](https://journals.asm.org/doi/10.1128/mmbr.00022-25)]
    
- **Web platforms and health informatics tools**: MoEPH for phage-host prediction in health informatics[[frontiersin](https://www.frontiersin.org/journals/microbiology/articles/10.3389/fmicb.2025.1634705/full)]
    
- **Experimental integration**: CRISPRi-ART enables programmable protein knockdown to highlight essential phage proteins; AI-generated phages are experimentally validated in lab dishes; genetic screens (RB-TnSeq, Dub-seq, CRISPRi) are used to train ML models for receptor prediction[[innovativegenomics](https://innovativegenomics.org/news/tool-phage-genomes/)]
    

Many studies integrate ML predictions with experimental validation cycles, enabling rapid design–test–learn workflows.[[pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih](https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC12149144/)]